From: Mitch Williams <mitch.a.williams@intel.com>
Date: Wed, 9 Oct 2019 07:09:48 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 157/289] ice: write register with correct offset

commit 395594563b29fbcd8d9a4f0a642484e5d3bb6db1 upstream.

The VF_MBX_ARQLEN register array is per-PF, not global, so we should not
use the absolute VF ID as an index. Instead, use the per-PF VF ID.

This fixes an issue with VFs on PFs other than 0 not seeing reset.

Signed-off-by: Mitch Williams <mitch.a.williams@intel.com>
Tested-by: Andrew Bowers <andrewx.bowers@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Jeff Kirsher <jeffrey.t.kirsher@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Liwei Song <liwei.song@windriver.com>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/intel/ice/ice_virtchnl_pf.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/ice/ice_virtchnl_pf.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/ice/ice_virtchnl_pf.c
index 376ba0cd21fa..dace9b07de55 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/ice/ice_virtchnl_pf.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/ice/ice_virtchnl_pf.c
@@ -391,7 +391,7 @@ static void ice_trigger_vf_reset(struct ice_vf *vf, bool is_vflr, bool is_pfr)
 	 * by the time we get here.
 	 */
 	if (!is_pfr)
-		wr32(hw, VF_MBX_ARQLEN(vf_abs_id), 0);
+		wr32(hw, VF_MBX_ARQLEN(vf->vf_id), 0);
 
 	/* In the case of a VFLR, the HW has already reset the VF and we
 	 * just need to clean up, so don't hit the VFRTRIG register.
